from the Origins of Time -- tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere is a gentleness in the midst of savagery in Stuart Dischell’s fifth full-length collection of poetry. These poems are ever aware of the momentary grace of the present and the fleeting histories that precede the instants of time. Part elegist, part fabulist, part absurdist, Dischell writes at the edges of imagination, memory, and experience. By turns outwardly social and inwardly reflective, comic and remorseful, the beautifully crafted poems of Children with Enemies transfigure dread with a reluctant wisdom and come alive to the confusions and implications of what it means to be human.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPoetry. 7aPOETRY / General.2bisacsh  apoetry, american literature, poems, poets, collection, gentleness, savagery, momentary grace, fleeting histories, absurdist, fables, imagination, memory, childhood experiences, children, kids, youth, reflective, humorous, dread, wisdom, growing up, coming of age, humanity, mortality, human lives, forgiving, tenderness, generosity, emotions, personal.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226498621423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226498621/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles